There&#39;s no need for a standard URL format and really no need to directly
encode a terse query language in URLs. You can if you want of course, but
really most anything will do, like
/cars?registeredBefore=2006-09&registeredAfter=2000-03
The handy part is using a standard form that generates the URL - HTML has
something that works. When more clients support WADL or some other format,
then the possible client-generated URLs will become richer.
In many applications, you can avoid teaching the client how to generate the
URLs by providing links and just teach the client how to find the links
within a document.


